          <text>
                    <body>
                              <pb n="1"/>
                              <p rend="align(right)">
                                        <placeName>St. Thomas</placeName>
                                        <date>May 1<hi rend="sup">st</hi> 5608(48)</date>
                              </p>
                              <p>My dear friend</p>
                              <p rend="indent(2)">I avail myself of the first<lb/> trip of the
                                        Steamer hence to <placeName>N. Y.</placeName> to drop
                                        you<lb/> a line acknowledging your last, assuring<lb/> you
                                        of <persName>Mrs. Nathan's</persName> and my good
                                        health,<lb/> and cherishing the hope that this will meet
                                        you<lb/> and all our friends in the full enjoyment of<lb/>
                                        that blessing.</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">Nothing that can be in any way<lb/> interesting
                                        does it fall to my lot to inform you<lb/> of. Political
                                        revolutions bring about commercial<lb/> ones, and this
                                        little depot, for the manufactures<lb/> and productions of
                                                  <placeName>Europe</placeName> and
                                                  <placeName>America</placeName>, is much<lb/>
                                        affected by the stir which nations are making<lb/> to obtain
                                        from Kings and priests the liberty, rights,<lb/> and
                                        privileges of which they have, until now, been<lb/> cruelly
                                                  depauded<add>?</add>. The events in the
                                                  <placeName>eastern hemisphere</placeName><lb/> and
                                        those in <placeName>Venezuela</placeName> are bringing our
                                        merchants to<lb/> the ground. Of course every one must
                                        suffer in<lb/> the general stagnations. The Synagogue is
                                        losing many<lb/> reliable members who are quitting this for
                                                  <placeName>America</placeName>,<lb/> and I suffer
                                        among the number in the <add>?</add><lb/> of my income. In a
                                        year the Synagogue will be<lb/> too poor to support any one
                                        I have a mere Reader</p>
                              <pb n="2"/>
                              <p>were it not for the School my income as<lb/> minister would not
                                        keep me in board and lodging.<lb/> I am obliged to toil in
                                        that laborious profession<lb/> as before, when, I hoped
                                        that, after leaving <placeName>Jamaica</placeName>,<lb/> I
                                        should not be again obliged to resume it.</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">There is little or no improvement in<lb/>
                                        spiritual matters. Sometimes, I am half inclined<lb/> to
                                        blame myself as the cause of want of progress,<lb/> were the
                                        character of the people not so well known.<lb/> There is too
                                        much <add>Hebrew</add> here. It requires a being<lb/> of
                                        greater capability than I possess to effect any
                                        thorough<lb/> good. Thanks be to God we are quiet. I am
                                        grateful<lb/> for small things in despair of accomplishing
                                                  <add>?</add><lb/>
                                        <add>?</add>. I have still<add>?</add> the rage for violent
                                        changes,<lb/> and even our friend <persName>Wolff</persName>
                                        is becoming orthodox.<lb/> The field of operation was better
                                        in <placeName>Jamaica</placeName>. I shall<lb/> never affect
                                        as much here as I did there. Still<lb/>
                                        <persName>Carillon's</persName> mad schemes are silenced for
                                        the <add>?</add>,<lb/> and the accomplishing so much is an
                                        evidence<lb/> of the successful result of my ministry.
                                        People<lb/> are more strict in pot and kettle than formerly
                                        there<lb/> is good attendance at the Synagogues on
                                        Sabbath,<lb/> and holy days, and the children generally are
                                        learning<lb/> Hebrew, and religion. The girls generally are
                                        studying<lb/> the sacred language, and several of them show
                                        great<lb/> proficiency.</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">A most <add>?</add> calamity has lately</p>
                              <pb n="3"/>
                              <p>befallen us, and it is my duty, as a minister of<lb/>
                                        <placeName>Israel</placeName> to inform you of it. Incest
                                        has been com-<lb/>mitted, between brother and sister, and
                                        the fruit of<lb/> it was brought forth to the disgrace of us
                                        all. The<lb/> parties have left the
                                                  <placeName>Island</placeName>, had they not, the
                                        General<lb/> would have sent them in chains to
                                                  <placeName>Copenhagen</placeName>. The<lb/> young
                                        man who acted this abominably received<lb/> a <hi
                                                  rend="underline">German</hi> education. I doubt by
                                        this mean to cast<lb/> a slur on
                                                  <placeName>Germany</placeName>, but on the parties
                                        who undertake<lb/> to teach without making religion the
                                        basis of instruction.<lb/> When Jewish parents send their
                                        children to a Jew<lb/> who has married a Christian, and yet
                                        who is a<lb/> Parnass of the <placeName>Hamburg</placeName>
                                        Temple, who breakfasts on<lb/>
                                        <date>Kippur</date> and then goes in solemn mockery to
                                        ask<lb/> atonement for his sins, what can be the result.
                                        The<lb/> unprincipled teacher will make a corrupt
                                                  <del>pu</del><lb/> pupil as in the present
                                        instance. <persName>Dr Fr√§nkel</persName><lb/> was the
                                        master, <persName>Mr. David Pretto</persName> son of
                                                  <persName>Jacob Pretto</persName><lb/> the pupil!
                                        The parents of the wretched children<lb/> are gone to the
                                                  <placeName>states</placeName> the incestuous
                                                  <add>?</add> wish the<lb/> guilty daughter are
                                        with them. God grant they may<lb/> never attempt to marry
                                        the child (a boy) in the<lb/> Jewish family. I write this
                                        for your Guidance<lb/> should they come to
                                                  <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>. The child
                                        has<lb/> not been circumcised, as they went away before</p>
                              <pb n="4"/>
                              <p>the eighth day. It has afflicted every one of<lb/> us. We hang down
                                        our heads with shame.</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">I was lately in <placeName>Jamaica</placeName>,
                                        and was<lb/> warmly welcomed. Whilst there, somebody
                                        told<lb/> me that the <placeName>N. O.</placeName>
                                        congregation had written me an<lb/> invitation to come and
                                        be their minister, but if so,<lb/> the letter has never
                                        reached my hands. <persName>Carillon</persName><lb/> applied
                                        to me to give him letters of introduction<lb/> and
                                        recommendation in order to obtain the<lb/> situation. I
                                        declined doing so, and gave him<lb/> as my reasons, his
                                        uniform bad conduct in <add>?</add><lb/> dissension and
                                        propagating improper and heterodox<lb/> doctrine. His
                                        eloquence did not move me. I<lb/> also refused to preach for
                                        him in <placeName>Spanish Town</placeName>, as<lb/> I would
                                        not aid him in the principle of sending<lb/> round the
                                        begging box for his benefit.</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">Pray give my best respects to <persName>Miss<lb/>
                                                  Gratz</persName> and all her family; to my friends
                                                  <persName>Mrs Hart</persName><lb/> and
                                                  <persName>Miss Louisa</persName>, <persName>Mr
                                                  Abr. Hart</persName> &amp; family, <persName>Mr
                                                  Peixotto</persName><lb/> your good land lady and
                                                  <persName>Miss Couzens</persName>, if she be
                                                  <persName>miss<lb/> Couzens</persName> still, and
                                        all my kind well wishers, send<lb/> me 100 of the Roads of
                                        faith. I hope you corrected<lb/> any errors without regard
                                        to my vanity or self-<lb/>love. Wishing you success in all
                                        your undertakings<lb/> in which <persName>Mrs
                                                  Nathan</persName> and family <add>?</add>.</p>
                              <p rend="indent(5)">I am</p>
                              <p rend="indent(5)">as ever</p>
                              <p rend="indent(5)">Truly &amp; sincerely yours</p>
                              <p rend="indent(5)">
                                        <persName role="author">M N Nathan</persName>
                              </p>
